{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Ticket creation-channel provenance\n\n## Context\n\nAuditors and maintainers can already inspect actor, environment, imported source identifiers, and external bindings, but ticket state does not identify the interface that produced the original CREATE event. That leaves debugging dependent on mutable tags and indirect clues when answering whether a ticket entered through the CLI, MCP server, Python library, Jira reconciler, or NDJSON import.\n\nThe current code has two creation seams. Local surfaces converge on src/rebar/_commands/composer.py:create_core through CLI and library/MCP wrappers, while Jira inbound creation composes CREATE data in src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py. Jira-created placeholder identities leave the direct Jira seam through _ensure_inbound_assignee_identity -> rebar.ensure_identity_for -> create_identity_core -> create_core, so that call explicitly overrides the local Python default with jira. Outbound Jira bind/sync operations are not creation events and never rewrite genesis provenance. Existing source_* import provenance in composer.py and reducer/_processors.py is prior art for additive CREATE metadata, but it answers where an imported record came from rather than which local ingress created it.\n\n## Why\n\nCreation channel is a single immutable audit dimension. Recording it on the genesis event gives auditors a direct answer without redefining actor, environment, external ID, assignee, or later mutation provenance. The chosen additive contract fits the event-sourced model, keeps old event logs readable, and avoids unreliable call-stack or tag inference for new writes.\n\n## Architecture Decisions\n\n- Add creation_channel to CREATE data and compiled ticket state with the closed compact vocabulary cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown.\n- Every live producer declares its channel at its entry boundary. The shared core carries and validates the declared internal value; it does not inspect the call stack. Direct public Python calls default to python.\n- New writes always record a concrete non-unknown value. Historical records without the field project jira only when all creation-stable signals agree: ticket_id starts with \"jira-\", author equals LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR (the exact literal \"reconciler\"), and env_id equals LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID (the exact literal \"reconciler\"). Define both constants in src/rebar/reducer/_version.py. inbound_translate._event_meta performs the absolute package import (from rebar.reducer._version import LEGACY_JIRA_AUTHOR, LEGACY_JIRA_ENV_ID) inside its function body, following the module's established late-import pattern, and the reducer imports the same symbols normally. This does not depend on sibling reconciler package context and is pinned by an isolated spec-load contract test. Missing/None signals or legacy events written under REBAR_AUTHOR/REBAR_ENV_ID overrides intentionally project unknown. Successful projections also carry creation_channel_inferred: true.\n- The inference marker is present only when true. ticket_state.schema.json encodes that rule formally as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit the key. It is diagnostic metadata, not a security attestation.\n- Import creates a new local ticket through the import channel. Existing source_id, source_created_at, source_author, and source_env continue to describe the source record; an exported source creation_channel is not reused as the new local channel.\n- Jira outbound bind/sync events preserve the already-reduced creation_channel and never supply a replacement value; only the inbound materialization CREATE and its placeholder-identity side effect declare jira.\n- Compaction preserves creation_channel and creation_channel_inferred inside SNAPSHOT.data.compiled_state. The SNAPSHOT envelope continues to describe the compactor, not the ticket creator. SNAPSHOT-only replay and snapshot rebuild must reproduce the same creation provenance as full-log replay.\n- The public change is additive. Older readers ignore the new CREATE keys; newer readers return unknown for non-Jira legacy records. The MVP deliberately has no writer-only configuration switch or intermediate binary mode; attribution defects are recovered by pausing the affected creation ingress at the deployment boundary and rolling forward. The only binary rollback is a full downgrade to the immediately pre-feature binary, which hides the field and has an explicit first-compaction DATA LOSS RISK. Before deploying the old binary, operators must stop every scheduled or manual rebar compact invocation and keep compaction/event retirement stopped for the entire downgrade window; re-enable it only after the new reader/compactor returns. Post-rollback schema state is deterministic: (a) a ticket with a new-code SNAPSHOT retains creation_channel if replayed because process_snapshot restores unknown compiled_state keys and the old strip policy removes only updated_at plus signature; (b) an old-binary first compaction of raw creation-bearing CREATE events would produce a SNAPSHOT without creation_channel, which is why compaction is prohibited during the window; (c) a never-compacted ticket retains the value in its CREATE event, although the old reader hides it. Notify downstream show/list/export consumers before any full downgrade and document this matrix plus the unconditional compaction pause in operator guidance.\n- No configuration switch or free-form channel extension is added. A future ingress such as a GitHub reconciler extends the closed vocabulary deliberately.\n\n## Scope\n\nIN:\n- CREATE writer plumbing for CLI, MCP, Python, Jira inbound, and NDJSON import, plus outbound Jira non-rewrite behavior.\n- All CREATE-backed helper flows, including ideas, identities, and session logs, attributed to the interface that invoked them.\n- Reducer projection, public ticket-state/output schemas, typed surfaces, export behavior, and documentation.\n- Conservative Jira-only historical inference with false-positive controls.\n- Compaction, SNAPSHOT-only replay, and snapshot rebuild durability.\n\nOUT:\n- Per-mutation provenance, actor/environment/external-ID redesign, cryptographic proof of channel, stack inspection, retroactive event rewrites, analytics dashboards, creation-channel list filters, subchannels for individual commands, and arbitrary custom strings.\n\n## Decomposition and Sequencing\n\nThree child stories deliver independently testable audit increments in dependency order:\n1. 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 — define the contract and expose correct local CLI, MCP, and Python attribution.\n2. e622-a596-3ceb-4f74 — add Jira/import attribution and conservative legacy Jira inference; depends on 6fe2.\n3. 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 — prove and preserve recorded, inferred, and unknown values through compaction and SNAPSHOT replay/rebuild; depends on e622.\n\nThe stories share reducer surfaces and therefore run sequentially through depends_on links. This is a multi-story feature and should use a Gerrit feature branch named feature/creation-channel-provenance; each child lands there through both review votes, followed by one gated no-ff merge change to main.\n\n## Risks and Mitigations\n\n- Missed producer path: enumerate every create_core and direct CREATE writer call site and pin each public facade/helper with a behavioral test.\n- False historical attribution: require the exact three-signal Jira predicate and add near-miss negative cases; never infer CLI, MCP, Python, or import.\n- Snapshot data loss: assert the fields inside compiled_state after source CREATE retirement and test rebuild_snapshot_from_full_log separately.\n- Contract drift: define the enum once, validate at writer boundaries, and reference the same vocabulary from the JSON schema and documentation.\n- Compatibility: keep the change additive and optional on stored historical events; no migration or destructive rewrite is performed.\n- Downgrade first-compaction loss: the MVP has no writer-only binary mode. Roll forward from attribution defects; before a full binary downgrade, stop every rebar compact invocation and keep event retirement paused until the new reader/compactor returns. Document the three-state compiled_state matrix.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- Auditors can distinguish cli, mcp, python, jira, and import creation through existing show/list/export state projections.\n- Historical Jira records are labeled jira with creation_channel_inferred=true only when the deterministic predicate matches; all other legacy records report unknown.\n- Every CREATE-backed ticket/entity helper reports the invoking interface rather than its internal implementation path.\n- Compaction and snapshot rebuild preserve the exact channel and inference marker after original events are retired.\n- The public schema and documentation define the vocabulary, default/fallback semantics, import behavior, and diagnostic trust boundary.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] CLI, MCP, plus direct Python creation report cli, mcp, plus python respectively across standard tickets, ideas, identities, plus session logs. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/facades/test_creation_channel.py -k \"cli or mcp or python\".\n- [ ] Newly materialized Jira issues plus reconciler-created placeholder identities report jira. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_creation_channel.py -k inbound_recorded.\n- [ ] Outbound Jira binding or synchronization preserves the existing local creation channel. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_creation_channel.py -k outbound.\n- [ ] NDJSON import reports import while retaining source_* record provenance. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/io/test_creation_channel.py -k import.\n- [ ] Legacy Jira inference fires only for the exact three-signal predicate; every near miss reports unknown without creation_channel_inferred. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_creation_channel.py -k legacy.\n- [ ] TicketState schemas, generated types, show/list/search projections, plus exported NDJSON expose the six-value enum with a const-true optional inference marker. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_ticket_state.py tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_outputs.py tests/interfaces/io/test_export_ndjson.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check.\n- [ ] Recorded or inferred values survive normal compaction after folded CREATE retirement. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py -k \"recorded or inferred\".\n- [ ] Legacy-SNAPSHOT fallback, SNAPSHOT-only replay, partial-horizon compaction, plus snapshot rebuild return the specified recorded/inferred/unknown projection. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_creation_channel_compaction.py tests/scripts/reducer/test_reducer_snapshot.py.\n- [ ] Every child story reports status closed in the shared store. Prove with uv run rebar show 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41 | jq -e '.status == \"closed\"' && uv run rebar show e622-a596-3ceb-4f74 | jq -e '.status == \"closed\"' && uv run rebar show 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87 | jq -e '.status == \"closed\"'.\n- [ ] Each child ticket trailer is present on origin/main after the gated feature-branch merge. Prove with git log origin/main --format=%B | grep -q \"rebar-ticket: 6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41\" && git log origin/main --format=%B | grep -q \"rebar-ticket: e622-a596-3ceb-4f74\" && git log origin/main --format=%B | grep -q \"rebar-ticket: 568c-b44b-7e2b-4d87\".\n- [ ] docs/event-schema.md plus docs/output-schemas.md define CREATE/SNAPSHOT placement, the enum, Jira inference, import semantics, plus the distinction from actor/environment/source_* provenance. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py && make lint.\n- [ ] docs/concurrency.md defines the full-downgrade three-state schema matrix. It requires every rebar compact invocation to remain stopped for the entire downgrade window. Prove with uv run pytest -q tests/interfaces/contracts/test_schema_coverage.py && make lint."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784262923512706001,"uuid":"84ef9587-295b-48b3-8d0d-9509e6f35606"}